Title: An Act to Enable the Maine Pilotage Commission to Oversee Pilots
Official Title: An Act to Enable the Maine Pilotage Commission to Oversee Pilots
Number of Sections: 1
Source: versions - Documents and Disposition
Media Type: application/pdf
Strikethrough Detection: 3 sections found

================================================================================

Section 1:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST SPECIAL SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1874
H.P. 1245 House of Representatives, May 5, 2025
Operating in Portland Harbor
Received by the Clerk of the House on May 1, 2025. Referred to the Committee on Marine
Resources pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed pursuant to Joint Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative CROCKETT of Portland.
Cosponsored by Representatives: EATON of Deer Isle, MONTELL of Gardiner, PARRY of
Arundel, Senator: DUSON of Cumberland.
Printed on recycled paper
1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 38 MRSA §85-B, sub-§3, as enacted by PL 1999, c. 355, §4, is amended to
3 read:
4 3. Coastal zones. "Coastal zones" means the 3 areas of Maine coastal waters relevant
5 to the commission membership, Calais to Schoodic Point, Schoodic Point to Port Clyde,
6 Southport Island and Port Clyde Southport Island to Kittery, excepting the port of Portland
7 and Casco Bay.
8 Sec. 2. 38 MRSA §86-A, sub-§3, as repealed and replaced by PL 1987, c. 689, §1,
9 is amended to read:
10 3. Portland harbor Harbor. Those waters specifically governed by the Board of
11 Harbor Commissioners for the Portland Harbor of Portland, except that the commission
12 retains those duties set forth in section 90 as they relate to pilots operating in such waters.
13 This section is not intended to confer jurisdiction or duties upon the commission with
14 respect to the activities of docking masters overseen by the Board of Harbor
15 Commissioners for Portland Harbor.
16 Sec. 3. 38 MRSA §87-A, sub-§1, ¶E, as amended by PL 2011, c. 14, §2, is further
17 amended to read:
18 E. All military ships navigating the Kennebec River to and from the Bath Iron Works
19 Corporation for the purpose of accomplishing overhaul, repair, post shakedown
20 availability and sea trials; and
21 Sec. 4. 38 MRSA §87-A, sub-§1, ¶F, as amended by PL 2015, c. 14, §1, is further
22 amended to read:
23 F. Noncommercial foreign vessels with overall length of under 253 feet., except in the
24 case of Portland Harbor; and
25 Sec. 5. 38 MRSA §87-A, sub-§1, ¶G is enacted to read:
26 G. In the case of Portland Harbor, noncommercial foreign vessels under 350 gross tons
27 for yacht or recreational purposes and noncommercial American vessels under 350
28 gross tons under registry for yacht or recreational purposes.
29 Sec. 6. P&SL 1981, c. 98, §5, sub-§2, as amended by PL 2011, c. 498, §2, is
30 repealed and the following is enacted in its place:
31 2. Operation as pilot. The rates, licensure, apprenticeship, continuing education,
32 fees, safety and other activities related to pilots operating upon the waters subject to the
33 jurisdiction of the Board of Harbor Commissioners for Portland Harbor must be overseen
34 and regulated by the Maine Pilotage Commission pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes,
35 Title 38, chapter 1, subchapter 3. This section is not intended to limit any authority
36 otherwise maintained by the Board of Harbor Commissioners for Portland Harbor to
37 oversee and regulate the activities of docking masters operating on waters subject to the
38 jurisdiction of the Board of Harbor Commissioners for Portland Harbor, except that such
39 activities may not include the service of actively piloting under the jurisdiction of the Maine
40 Pilotage Commission.
Page 1 - 132LR0691(01)
1 Sec. 7. Rulemaking by Maine Pilotage Commission. Within 6 months of the
2 effective date of this Act, the Maine Pilotage Commission shall commence rulemaking
3 with regard to Chapter 1 of its rules to adopt in substantially the same form, for a period of
4 time at least 24 months in duration, the provisions contained in Section 17.0 of the rules of
5 the Board of Harbor Commissioners for Portland Harbor as of the effective date of this Act
6 as they relate to the licensure, apprenticeship, continuing education, safety and other
7 provisions in Section 17.0 of those rules as they relate to pilots operating in Portland Harbor
8 as long as any fees assessed upon pilots operating in Portland Harbor are consistent with
9 fees assessed upon pilots subject to the jurisdiction of the commission. In adopting these
10 initial rules, this provision does not limit the ability of the commission to organize the
11 foregoing provisions and standards into the commission's existing rules as long as the
12 application of these rules to pilots operating in Portland Harbor are substantially similar to
13 the provisions in Section 17.0 of the rules of the Board of Harbor Commissioners for
14 Portland Harbor. Following the 24-month time period after initial adoption of the rules
15 described in this section, the commission may further amend the rules governing pilots
16 operating in Portland Harbor without regard to consistency with Section 17.0 of the rules
17 of the Board of Harbor Commissioners for Portland Harbor. Rules adopted pursuant to this
18 section are routine technical rules as described in the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 5,
19 chapter 375, subchapter 2-A. Commencing on the effective date of this Act and pending
20 final adoption of rules pursuant to this section, pilots operating in Portland Harbor are
21 subject to the jurisdiction of the commission according to any terms or conditions in place
22 during such time period as duly authorized by the Board of Harbor Commissioners for
23 Portland Harbor, other than fee assessments upon pilots in Portland Harbor, if any, which
24 must be consistent with any fees assessed by the commission upon other pilots subject to
25 the commission's jurisdiction.
26 Sec. 8. Rulemaking by Board of Harbor Commissioners for Portland
27 Harbor. Within 6 months of the effective date of this Act, the Board of Harbor
28 Commissioners for Portland Harbor shall commence rulemaking to ensure that the board's
29 rules are consistent with this Act.
30 SUMMARY
3311 This bill transfers jurisdiction over pilots operating in Portland Harbor from the Board
3322 of Harbor Commissioners for Portland Harbor to the Maine Pilotage Commission.
33 It also changes the description of the coastal zones in the laws governing the Maine
34 Pilotage Commission and, in the case of Portland Harbor, provides that certain vessels are
35 exempt from the laws governing the Maine Pilotage Commission.
Page 2 - 132LR0691(01)
